44
00:06:13,720 --> 00:06:29,401
I mean, of course, that's not why I think it's important to me, or I don't know if this is how it was to Ishmael, but we've got to read it and see that lots of interesting things are going on here, starting on 402.

45
00:06:31,481 --> 00:06:39,241
So, starting at the third paragraph in chapter 94, he's talking about the new job he's got.

46
00:06:39,241 --> 00:06:40,680
It was a little way down.

47
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:45,681
It was our business to squeeze these lumps back into fluid.

48
00:06:45,680 --> 00:06:55,841
So, there they had this big tub of the sperm out of Moby Dick that they were, why I don't know, he doesn't tell us, squeezing it back into liquid.

49
00:06:55,840 --> 00:07:04,241
But on 403, he tells us that it completely changed his mood.

50
00:07:04,241 --> 00:07:13,281
He'd been in this mood of monomania that he had taken over from Ahab, and Ahab's curse and search had become his.

51
00:07:13,281 --> 00:07:30,561
And now he gets rid of that on 403 and gets switched into another mood, not again by choosing, but by being drawn in, he's drawn into the mood as far from Ahab as you can get, about 15 lines down on 403.

52
00:07:30,560 --> 00:07:36,481
For the time I lived as in a musky meadow, I forgot all about our horrible oath.

53
00:07:36,481 --> 00:07:43,601
That's the other mood, when Ahab dipped the harpoon in blood and made them all swear to go after Moby Dick.

54
00:07:44,881 --> 00:07:49,520
In that inexpressible sperm, I washed my hands and my heart of it.

55
00:07:49,521 --> 00:07:56,401
I mean, in other words, I completely got out of that mood, and I completely got into this mood.

56
00:07:56,961 --> 00:07:59,680
So he was in sync with Ahab.

57
00:07:59,680 --> 00:08:01,601
What's he in sync with now?

58
00:08:01,600 --> 00:08:09,440
Well, he's in sync with all the other people who, or the other subgroup of sailors from the boat.

59
00:08:09,440 --> 00:08:14,561
I don't know how they got picked or who they were, who were doing this job together.

60
00:08:14,560 --> 00:08:20,641
So in the middle of 403, I squeezed that sperm till I myself almost melted into it.

61
00:08:20,641 --> 00:08:24,080
I squeezed that sperm until a strange sort of insanity came over me.

62
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:25,920
This was this very strange mood.

63
00:08:25,920 --> 00:08:32,680
I found myself unwittingly squeezing my co-laborer's' hands in it, mistaking their hands for the gentle gobules.

64
00:08:33,001 --> 00:08:40,601
Such an abounding, affectionate, friendly, loving feeling did this avocation beget.

65
00:08:40,601 --> 00:08:43,801
And this is sort of friendship at its best.

66
00:08:44,361 --> 00:08:49,081
And it's related to this friendship he has for Quequeg.

67
00:08:49,481 --> 00:08:58,121
That's the only other time we hear about this kind of special loving mood that you can get into that's very important.

68
00:08:58,440 --> 00:09:10,121
It certainly seems to be erotic, and it certainly seems to be sentimental, but he quickly gives it a broader and very interesting meaning.

69
00:09:10,121 --> 00:09:12,521
And that's at the bottom of the page.

70
00:09:12,521 --> 00:09:25,641
Remember, the subject we're interested in is: can you find meaning in a world without onto theology, without the supreme being and the total order?

71
00:09:25,800 --> 00:09:27,480
In short, without Dante.

72
00:09:27,721 --> 00:09:30,761
That's the guy in our course that stands for this.

73
00:09:30,761 --> 00:09:44,521
And the answer is yes, but only if you don't insist on total, eternal fulfillment the way you're supposed to get it if you stare at God at the end of the divine comedy.

74
00:09:44,521 --> 00:09:46,041
So here's what he says.

75
00:09:46,040 --> 00:09:48,441
Second line at the bottom paragraph.

76
00:09:48,440 --> 00:10:01,561
For now, since by many prolonged or repeated experiences, I have perceived that in all cases, man must eventually lower or at least shift his conceit of attainable felicity.

77
00:10:01,560 --> 00:10:02,841
That's a mouthful.

78
00:10:02,840 --> 00:10:09,801
His conceit of attainable felicity means he's got to lower his demand for what happiness is.

79
00:10:10,920 --> 00:10:13,001
What kind of happiness you can attain.

80
00:10:13,001 --> 00:10:20,961
That is, you can't have total, eternal, unconditional, and absolute fulfillment.

81
00:10:21,281 --> 00:10:27,921
So you have to place it, not placing it anywhere in the intellect or the fancy, but in.

82
00:10:27,920 --> 00:10:41,361
And now comes a whole list of particular, temporary, sometimes short-term, sometimes long-term, local-ish forms of satisfaction.

83
00:10:41,361 --> 00:10:56,080
The wife, and I'll keep giving you sort of, just so you see what's going on, each of these is going to be a mood, and each of these is going to be related to some goddess or god in the pantheon, roughly the Greeks.

84
00:10:56,320 --> 00:11:02,160
It doesn't map completely, but there's the wife, that's the domestic mood, that's Hera.

85
00:11:02,160 --> 00:11:03,041
The heart.

86
00:11:03,040 --> 00:11:14,401
I take the heart is the friendship that he's been having because it's this kind of warm, very affectionate feeling that you can have for your fellow human beings.

87
00:11:14,401 --> 00:11:19,521
The bed, I take that to be sex and Aphrodite and the erotic.

88
00:11:19,521 --> 00:11:21,761
The table, it's not, of course.

89
00:11:22,001 --> 00:11:23,361
