97
00:11:51,121 --> 00:11:52,080
I don't know either.

98
00:11:52,080 --> 00:11:52,960
But it's all right.

99
00:11:52,961 --> 00:11:54,481
I'm talking about it again.

100
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:56,160
It's another one.

101
00:11:56,481 --> 00:12:08,361
It's more short-lived, but it's a local, temporary world around the dinner in which all these people are brought together and they're all brought out in their best.

102
00:12:09,320 --> 00:12:18,521
Heidegger has this idea that you can make these self-contained worlds which have their own meaning and bring things out in their own most, as he puts it.

103
00:12:18,521 --> 00:12:27,481
So fathers and mothers and children and vegetables and all are brought out at their best when the dinner comes out right.

104
00:12:27,481 --> 00:12:29,721
And that's another one of these things.

105
00:12:29,721 --> 00:12:35,881
It's not like staring into God in the divine comedy, but it is a kind of happiness.

106
00:12:35,881 --> 00:12:39,320
The table, the saddle, that's for horse people.

107
00:12:39,641 --> 00:12:41,321
My daughter was one of them.

108
00:12:41,320 --> 00:12:44,201
And that goes, Captain Kirk obviously was one of them.

109
00:12:44,361 --> 00:12:48,281
We talked about how that's when he went to his sort of retirement.

110
00:12:48,440 --> 00:12:50,521
It was some beautiful horses.

111
00:12:50,840 --> 00:12:52,521
The fireside.

112
00:12:52,840 --> 00:12:55,961
The fireside is a funny one.

113
00:12:56,840 --> 00:13:01,160
I'm having this deja retreat that I, oh, I talked about this in another lecture.

114
00:13:01,160 --> 00:13:04,601
I gave it another state in another week.

115
00:13:04,600 --> 00:13:06,281
I don't think I did.

116
00:13:06,281 --> 00:13:08,521
I tell you about the foyer?

117
00:13:09,001 --> 00:13:17,721
Okay, the fireside is interesting because it's the example of these kinds of focal practices.

118
00:13:17,721 --> 00:13:20,840
Focal practices is what a guy named Borgman calls them.

119
00:13:20,840 --> 00:13:45,201
There's no reason why you should know about Albert Borgman, but he did write a very good book, and it was about the way focal practices are different than what he calls the just enjoying commodities, where you just get the result and you don't have to do any work and you don't have to have any skill, and it always gives you just the thing you want, and nothing more or less.

120
00:13:44,040 --> 00:13:50,800
So, fast food is the commodity version of the cultivation of the table.

121
00:13:51,440 --> 00:13:55,840
And in the case of the foyer, it means in French, fireplace.

122
00:13:55,840 --> 00:13:58,241
The fireplace is the foyer.

123
00:13:58,241 --> 00:14:13,441
It's the focus because once it was the focus of the family, in which they had to have the skill for cutting the wood, for keeping the fire going, and they had to sit around it to keep warm and to cook and presumably to read the Bible or whatever they did in those days.

124
00:14:15,040 --> 00:14:21,361
And therefore, the fireplaces are sort of the model or a kind of focal practice.

125
00:14:22,241 --> 00:14:24,720
And they turn into commodities in a funny way.

126
00:14:24,721 --> 00:14:32,321
That's what I suddenly stopped and remembered that I told this to some other group, and I'll tell it to you too, because it's sort of pathetic and funny.

127
00:14:32,641 --> 00:14:34,881
My daughter shows up in this again.

128
00:14:34,881 --> 00:14:44,241
I mean, the idea that sitting in front of the fireplace is the way to sort of be when you're at home, she had that.

129
00:14:44,241 --> 00:14:55,281
Unfortunately, we didn't have any fireplace, but she instead always did her homework and petted the cat and talked to her friends sitting on the hot air vent in the floor in the living room.

130
00:14:55,681 --> 00:15:07,840
And that's what's left of the fireplace as it's turning into a commodity, where the heat just comes there and it doesn't have any focus and it doesn't take any skill and it doesn't unite anybody around it.

131
00:15:08,161 --> 00:15:18,241
And the last pathetic thing I thought was, well, the next generation is going to have radiant heat in the floor and not even any hot air coming in through a vent, and that's the end of it.

132
00:15:18,241 --> 00:15:25,761
Heat will have turned completely from the spokes of the family into something so much of a commodity that nobody will even know.

133
00:15:25,761 --> 00:15:30,600
The room, the thermostat will do its job, and the room will stay the same temperature summer and winter.

134
00:15:30,921 --> 00:15:38,441
And there's a danger that all of these can be gotten rid of by being turned into commodities.

135
00:15:38,441 --> 00:15:40,200
The next one is the country.

136
00:15:40,360 --> 00:15:42,360
That means patriotism, I suppose.

137
00:15:42,360 --> 00:15:54,761
You could think of that as the Aeneas, or you could think of that as what Athena brings about in the Orestea, where the pride in Athens is the meaningful thing.

138
00:15:54,761 --> 00:16:17,640
So all of these, that list, is a list of somewhat meaningful practices which could still make your life worth living, but you can only have them if you lower your standards and don't insist that it be a complete knockout of the traditional Dante story.

139
00:16:17,961 --> 00:16:24,040
Okay, then that's what's so interesting about that particular chapter.

140
00:16:24,040 --> 00:16:32,761
And what's, I realized just yesterday that he's prepared you for this, or I mean, that would give much too much of a sense that he knows what he's doing.

141
00:16:33,001 --> 00:16:53,080
But something in him came out earlier that is related to this when on 102, when you get another one of these absolute people, the guy who doesn't think, who isn't insisting on an absolute relation to God, in fact, he's thinking about an absolute relation to nothing.

142
00:16:53,080 --> 00:17:03,320
That's Balkington, standing in the howling gale of the infinite, in the indefinite and the ungrounded, and not asking for any meaning.

143
00:17:03,320 --> 00:17:08,921
But for him, he doesn't want the port, the land.

144
00:17:08,921 --> 00:17:12,920
But here there's a good story about the land on 102 at the top.

145
00:17:12,921 --> 00:17:18,640
In the port is safety, comfort, hearthstone, there we go again, the fireplace.

146
00:17:14,120 --> 00:17:20,081
Supper, there's the table again.

147
00:17:20,400 --> 00:17:23,761
Warm blankets, friends, there's the love again.

148
00:17:23,761 --> 00:17:26,481
All that's kind to our mortalities.

149
00:17:26,481 --> 00:17:43,920
And it's not, notice, talk about the slavish land here and how nobody in their right mind would go and walk around on that turnpike earth with its landmarks all over and no indeterminate, no mystery.

150
00:17:43,921 --> 00:17:57,361
There is the side of Melville which really does appreciate a kind of much lowered but nonetheless satisfying and meaningful way of life.

151
00:17:57,360 --> 00:18:04,080
And it comes up there, and it certainly is, for him, a kind of sacred.

152
00:18:04,080 --> 00:18:14,241
So the fireplace and cultivating your dinner and all, and the Aphrodite erotic and all that can be sacred.

153
00:18:14,241 --> 00:18:33,200
And the way you can see it in this funny way on the bottom of 403, after he lists all these local moods, I keep wanting to say two of these, there is a mood, of course, I keep forgetting to say, which goes with each of these, whether it's the erotic mood or the domestic mood or the aggressive mood and so forth.

154
00:18:33,201 --> 00:18:37,040
All of this, he says, where is it now?

155
00:18:38,001 --> 00:18:44,800
I am ready, and after I perceived all this, I'm ready to squeeze case that is sperm eternally.

